    <div>
      <p> to view the video that was used to write this code go to:
    <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TPDz_84UJGw">YouTube Video</a>
    <br>
    <p> The goal of this script is to have the user input a number in the 'Prompt'
      box.  The javaScript Program will then run and test the 'UserInput' in a
      conditional loop.  Should the 'UserInput' be equal to the if statement
      it will display the corresponding alert.</P>
      <textarea>
          <script type="text/javascript">
            var userInput = Number(prompt("Please enter a number", ""));

              if (userInput === 1) {
                alert("Your number is one");
              }
              else if (userInput === 2) {
                alert("Your number is two");
              }
              else if (userInput === 3) {
                alert("Your number is three");
              }
              else if (userInput !=1 && userInput !=2 && userInput !=3) {
                alert("Your number is not between 1 and 3");
              }
            </script>
        </textarea>


      <p>An else if is used because if one of the 'if' statements is true, none of
      the other statements can be true.  So an else statement tells the javaScript
      program that it does not need to continue checking the other statements. </p>

      <br>
    </div>

    <script type="text/javascript">
    var userInput = Number(prompt("Please enter a number", ""));

    if (userInput === 1) {
      alert("Your number is one");
    }
    else if (userInput === 2) {
      alert("Your number is two");
    }
    else if (userInput === 3) {
      alert("Your number is three");
    }
    else if (userInput !=1 && userInput !=2 && userInput !=3) {
      alert("Your number is not between 1 and 3");
    }

</script>
